Geckskin: Super Adhesive

Posted on December 7, 2012 by Thomas Scully 


 Some things we see in nature we describe as phenomena because we cannot explain them.  One phenomenon for many years was the ability of geckos to stick to walls or other surfaces with great ease.  We’ve all probably wished for this “spider-man-like ability” at one time or another in our life but never been able to achieve it.  Recently, researchers at the University of Massachusettes have discovered what exactly gives geckos their ability to stick to various surfaces and have had success replication it in a new material called geckskin.
The secret behind geckos’ adhesive properties is what is known as “van der Waals” force.  Geckos’ feet have tiny hair-like structures on them which each have tiny flat ends called “spatulae.”  These spatulae give the geckos’ feet a much larger surface area than they would have without them.  Van der Waals force is the attraction that occurs between atoms and molecules.  Between small objects, this force is too minimal to apply, however objects with large surface areas have a much greater attraction due to this force.  The increased surface area of the geckos’ feet allows them to attract to surfaces and stick.  The researchers at the University of Massachusettes have successfully been able to replicate this in there design, geckskin.  This design could become very popular as it can support up to 700 pounds of weight with a very small square of geckskin.  It also leaves behind no residue as current sticky devices would, becuase of its application of van der Waals force in its design.  It works exactly like a gecko’s skin and supports huge amounts of weight relative to its size but it can be removed easily.
These designers have taken a page out of nature’s book and used biology to aid in their design and production of a new material that could be very popular soon.  More research and development is being done with this groundbreaking discovery and with some slight tweaks it could be put into mass production in the near future.  The possiblities to stick things together easily and effectively with no other effects or results is very appealling to a number of businesses and consumers and if a glove company picks up the design, who knows, maybe we’ll see some clothing that allows the wearer to be spider-man-like.  Whatever the future, this material is a very promising design.
http://www.wggb.com/2012/03/12/super-adhesive-inspired-by-a-reptile/
http://www.masslive.com/living/index.ssf/2012/04/umass_researchers_solve_gecko_superpower_mystery.html
http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2011/11/why-a-geckos-feet-can-stick-to-almost-anything/



