Smart Headlights: Making Rain and Snow seem Invisible

Posted on December 6, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

         
In a world where one of the biggest emphases around is placed on safety, and rightly so, many of the most sought after innovative designs are those which improve the safety of users.  People value their safety extremely highly and because of this fact there is incentive for designers to seek the safest form of design despite the extra cost.  People are always willing to pay a little extra for guaranteed extra safety.  One extremely common aspect of everyday life that can also be life threatening in extreme circumstances is driving a car or other vehicle.  In certain weather it can become dangerous to be driving due to road conditions or another aspect, sight impairment.  Imagine when you are driving at night and it starts raining.  The rain appears as illuminated drops falling from the sky that can be distracting or impairing to the eye while driving.  This has been a problem for drivers until now.
Professor Srinivasa Narasimhan of Carnegie Mellon University has been a leading developer of the smart headlight system.  It is designed to reduce or eliminate the glare from rain caused by headlights.  The system involves a high frequency camera which continuous takes pictures of the falling rain.  The system then sends these pictures to a computer which “applies a computer algorithm to predict where each bit of precipitation will be a few milliseconds later.”  This prediction system sends a signal to the headlights which automatically turn off the rays from the headlights that would intersect the path of the rain as each drop passes the point of intersectionand turns the rays back on after the drop passes.  Because the rays turned off at one moment are so small compared to the total rays projected, the headlights will not appear to have lost any brightness but the rain will be almost invisible to the driver.  The system is 100% reliable at very low speeds and as the vehicle’s speed increases, the system becomes less reliable; however, it is very reliable up to extreme speeds.  This is pretty good considering during rain or snowfall most people will not be driving very fast anyway.  This is a very good and effective design that improves safety in vehicles a good deal and may become a common aspect of vehicles for years to come.
http://www.technologyreview.com/news/428353/smart-headlights-see-through-rain-and-snow/
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kDT756kQrCI&noredirect=1
http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/2012/07/26/smart-headlights-let-drivers-see-through-rain-and-snow/



