Service Design

Posted on December 6, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

                                                   
Although it is a relatively young field in terms of the existence of it’s formal education, service design has always been developed among competing businesses as a way to improve and stand out.  You can find it today anywhere someone is trying to make your life easier or anywhere a product is tailored to appeal to specific needs or desires.  Every company or business applies it in some way or another because they have now come to realize that people will seek and always prefer something that makes them feel comfortable or at home.  “The backbone of this process is to understand the behavior of the customers, their needs and motivations.”  Companies now try to cater to the customers’ needs in order to gain their business.  The difficulty is in knowing and understanding what customers want before asking them.  Some people even believe this to be impossible.  How can a designer really know what service people will want?  In order to better understand how to incorporate service design, some designers go “undercover” in a service business and learn by example.  They practice and gain firsthand knowledge in how to serve people.
One company that has been successful in its service design is McDonald’s in France.  At one point in time, French citizens had no desire to incorporate McDonald’s into their lives or eat there at all.  They disliked the fast food restaurant’s presence in their country, but nowadays the average French customer at McDonald’s spends 3 times as much as the average American customer.  This change occurred because of McDonald’s service design which appealled to French interests.  The fast food restaurant changed its atmosphere.  It modeled itself after, Starbucks, a place frequented by French citizens.  Starbucks sought to create there locations “designed to provide customers with a third place; a place between home and work where they can go to relax or meet with friends.”  McDonald’s adapted this making the place less uniform and more relaxed and open environment to enjoy the company of friends.  They no longer appeared to treat customers as the same uniform person, but as individuals.  This attracted more people and, as a result, more business.
In conclusion, the ways to design for service are vast and variable, but the effects of a good service design are no small matter.  Many companies pride themselves and thrive on service design.  If the customer is the person you are looking to buy your product, doesn’t it make sense to design it to serve him?  The best designs incorporate this technique in order to make the customer feel at home.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Service_design
http://www.guardian.co.uk/service-design/service-science
http://designforservice.wordpress.com/



