Beaming Technology

Posted on November 1, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

This exciting new technology in the realm of social interaction is still in development process, but it could become very important in long distance communication one day.  The researchers and developers of this “beaming” technology notice, “Humans are social animals and, paradoxically, as telepresence technologies evolve they become more frustrating.”  This can be seen commonly in video calls as people understand they are not really with the person whose face they are seeing.  The idea behind beaming is that people need a more personal way of interacting across long distances to create the best effect and get the most out of the interaction.
The technology, as anyone can imagine, is incredibly advanced and requires even more study and advancement before it can be completely functional.  The device used requires the reception and transmition of multiple signals from two locations.  In the first location the person wears a transmitor that reads signals given by the person including facial expression, motion, body language, and other functions.  In the other location is a robotic avatar or a virtual avatar which receives the signals from the human and acts them out.  This second location also receives signals from the surrounding environment and transmit them back to the human on the other side.  This allows for a person to understand and react to everything in an environment without even being there.  Strides have been made and recently there was an experiment done using a small robotic avatar in a cage with a mouse.  The person controlling the robot used the signals transmitted to him to follow the mouse’s actions and people on the robot’s side confirmed the successful mimicry.
This technology still has a long way to go in every aspect but the idea of being able to “be” somewhere else without actually travelling there is appealing to a great deal of people and probably especially business men who need to conduct meetings across countries.  We may never reach the beaming capabilities in such science fiction stories as Star Trek, but this new technology is a step towards it and hopefully as step towards better and easier long distance communication.
http://www.devicemag.com/2012/11/01/beaming-technology-changes-level-of-human-animal-interaction/
http://www.gizmag.com/cordis-beaming/24769/
http://www.gizmag.com/human-rat-beaming-interaction/24834/



