Pipistrel Taurus G4

Posted on November 1, 2012 by Thomas Scully 


The Pipistrel Taurus G4 is a remarkable innovation in the world of flying.  The plane, which is remarkably similar to a glider in several ways, can hold 4 passengers including the two pilots.  It is powered entirely by electric power and won the NASA/CAFE green flight challenge, the prize for which was $1.35 million.  Although it is small and almost half of the plane’s weight is accounted for by the battery powering the engine, the technological opportunity presented by this plane shows that there may be a future in electronic powered aircraft.  The plane was able to travel 200 miles in 2 hours giving it an average speed of 100mph.
The plane itself weighs a little less than 2500 and the battery that powers it weighs just over 1000 pounds.  The lithium polymer battery generates 150 kilowatts which is an output of 200 horsepower.  The physical design of the plane with a wingspan of roughly 75 feet and two twin fuselages on either side of a central part where the battery is located makes the plane efficient but may not catch on as a guide for future plane designs.  The designers note that the Taurus G4 is more of a prototype in the way of electric powered planes and is not likely to ever be on the market.  It will, however, serve as a stepping stone to future developments in electronic air travel and greener air travel.
http://www.wired.com/autopia/2011/08/pipistrel-taurus-g4-electric/
http://blog.cafefoundation.org/?p=3291
http://inhabitat.com/pipistrel-introduces-the-worlds-most-powerful-electric-airplane/



