3-D Printing

Posted on November 1, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

3-D printing is a revolution in the way we produce various items.  It creates an easy and low effort way of creating objects.  Although the software and setup of the 3-D printer requires a great deal of time, work, and effort, once it is set up it makes the process of creating a part or object extremely simple.  Although it is still young in its existence, 3-D printing is well on its way to immensely changing how we create parts and products.
3-D printers operate with the use of a created or scanned CAD, or Computer Aided Design, file.  The computer uses this file and sends it to the the printer which then produces the image by laying it out layer by layer.  This process will naturally take more or less time depending on how complex the object is and because the object is produced layer by layer it requires the object to have at lest one flat surface.  The various types of machines can print using plastics, metals, and now even printing in concrete is developing.  As the process advances and can be applied to a wider range of materials it will become more prevalent and valuable to manufacturers.
The positives associated with 3-D printing are numerous.  One benefit would be how easily it can produce parts and objects.  This could prove a huge benefit for manufacturers as the technology develops.  They’re parts can be made in whatever shapes they can imagine and all they’ll have to do is send a signal to the printer to create it.  Researchers at Loughborough University in the United Kingdom are examining 3-D printing with concrete which could lead to huge advances in what can be printed.  The possibilities seem endless.
Some negatives include the fact that right now the majority of 3-D printers only produce very small items but there is a lot of room to expand and develop larger printers.  They also can take a long time to print, especially with very complicated designs which could lead to slow production of parts.  The biggest drawback in the design though may be the impact on personal production.  People can buy 3-D printers for their homes and although they are expensive, prices are dropping, and if people can produce their own products they may consume much less which will hurt the economy.  Another problem with personal production is what people can produce.  One point was made that all someone would need to do to produce a gun is find the design online and download it and that is possible.  3-D printers have produced operational guns which demonstrates that people could produce their own unregistered guns.  In reality most people will not do this, however, the possibility is there which could lead to problems.
Overall, if the production and use of 3-D printers is regulated and research continues to yield big results, I believe 3-D printing could become a key part of production of goods in the future.
http://3dprinting.com/what-is-3d-printing/
http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/with-a-3-d-printer-building-a-gun-at-home/
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EfbhdZKPHro&feature=player_detailpage



