Product Life Cycles

Posted on October 31, 2012 by Thomas Scully 


We have all seen this happen multiple times during our life and we will continue to see it as long as we live.  As long as there are new and innovative ideas and improvements in technology (and there always will be) a product will always experience the stages of the product life cycle.  Some products may experience longer time periods of certain stages but all will undoubtedly experience a rise in popularity and sales and then a decline in both.  The product life cycle is expected by all designers and although there are multiple views of the product life cycle the overall trend of it is constant.
One view of the product life cycle include the affectionate view which is the idea that life cycles occure because people always buy what looks sleek and new and what looks the best as designers are always improving the look of their designs.  Another view is the business view of product life cycles which operates under the idea that marketing and competition will create product life cycles as people desire the newest and best and will replace their old products with the new.
There are other views as well but what all the views share in common is the idea that the designers are the ones who have the most influence on product life cycles with how they design.  They can design with the intention of their product becoming obsolete quickly thus leaving room for them to design new products or they can design with the intention of a lasting design that may grow obsolete on its own or be forced into obselescence by new technologies.  The impact of product life cycles have created a great deal of waste and exhaustion of natural resources.  The debat has become whether it is better to design sustainably or with the intention of long life rather than designing to be obsolete and make money.  Ultimately it is in the hands of the designers and the companies but it is a fact that resources are depleting and eventually will run out with increased consumption.  Whether or not this will lead to increased shortening of product life cycles or lead to designing for longer product life cycles is still uncertain but the consequences of either will have massive effects on the world.
https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=cHN1LmVkdXxkZXNpZ24tdGhpbmtpbmd8Z3g6MjU1MmJiMGY5ZTc5YjM4Zg
http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/22/AR2008042202520.html
http://www.storyofstuff.org/movies-all/story-of-stuff/
http://people.hofstra.edu/geotrans/eng/ch5en/conc5en/productlifecycle.html



