Environmental/Sustainable Design

Posted on October 31, 2012 by Thomas Scully 


One hot button topic of the last decade has been environmental impact and whether or not we as humans are having a large negative impact on the environment.  Although it is less prevalent in discussions today, many people still see problems such as global warming or the exhaustion of natural resources as the world’s most pressing issues.  In order to combat these potential dangers to human existence engineers and designers are now incorporating a great deal more of sustainability in their designs.
Sustainability can be explained as “the philosophy of designing physical objects, the built environment, and services to comply with the principles of social, economic, and ecological sustainability. ”  It is a key idea in the preservation of natural resources and involves sustaining the existing environment while also creating a new building or whatever else is being designed.  Involved in sustainable design is the use of more natural energy to reduce energy costs and promote clean energy.  Many buildings incorporate large glass windows to allow for use of natural light for most of the day or motion sensor lights in rooms to ensure the lights are not left on and the energy wasted.  Along with this goes the development of solar, wind and other renewable energy sources which are very sustainable, however, as of now they are much more expensive than coal, natural gas, oil, and other current forms of producing energy.
Many buildings are also now incorporating green roofs which allow plant life to thrive on the tops of the buildings thus preserving the natural design of the area while also including new human design.  One example of commitment to developing sustainable buildings is at The Pennsylvania State University.  Many of Penn State’s newest buildings include green roofs, motion sensor lights, effective use of glass to reduce artificial light dependency, and other environmentally friendly and sustainable features.  It is this type of commitment that will improve design sustainability going forward.  An example of a design that is not extremely sustainable is the plastic bottle which requires the digging of landfills and is harmful to the environment if left in nature.  It can inhibit the growth of the natural plant and animal species of the are.  In essence it does not work with the environment, but against it.
Although strides have been made in the field of sustainability, there are still many more to be made.  More companies can become involved and more design fields can involve increased sustainability in their designs.  The result will be better use of natural resources and a much better environmental impact by humans.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sustainable_design
http://www.esf.org/activities/eurocores/completed-programmes/s3t/esf-nsf-workshop-in-pizay.html
http://atlas.aaas.org/index.php?part=2
http://www.nrel.gov/sustainable_nrel/about.html



