Emotions and Design

Posted on October 31, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

Many designers today are realizing that people do not always necessarily buy the product that does in fact work the most efficiently or have the cheapest price.  Many consumers purchase products that arouse strong emotional feelings within them.  Although it is hard to explain why emotions have such power of us as humans, it is without question that they do hold this power.  For designers to be successful they want to tap into this impulsive factor of consumption and give people an emotional attachment to their products.  One example of a powerful emotion in design is nostalgia.  Those products that make people feel nostalgic and remind them of past glory days and fun times are sold very easily.  One examples of important emotions in design are joy and fear.  One well said example of how fear controls us is as follows:
”
Imagine a plank 10 meters long and 1 meter wide. Place it on the ground. Can you walk on it? Of course – no problem. You can jump up and down, dance, and even walk along with your eyes shut. Now lift the plank 3 meters in the air. Can you walk on it? Yes, although more carefully.
What if the plank were 200 meters in the air? Most of us wouldn’t dare go near it, even though the act of walking along it and maintaining balance should be no more difficult than when on the ground. Why would a simple task suddenly become so difficult – impossible, even? Tell yourself all you want that if you can walk on the plank on the ground, you can still walk on it in the air. You still won’t walk along it, let alone jump and dance or, heaven forbid, close your eyes while walking. Fear dominates. (Norman, Emotion and Design)”
This shows that people will not go near a product they fear even if in another scenario they would be indifferent.
Aesthetics are very important in emtional design.  The sight of a nice looking object creates positive feelings toward that object and draws people to that object, just as something that looks ugly or unappealing will create negative feelings that cause people to stay away from that product.
One example of this used in design is in the “Bottoms Up Draft Beer Dispensing System” found on the site “Built to Love.”  This design creates positive feelings in customers because they enjoy just watching it work and therefore will purchase beer to see it operate.  It also creates a more efficient way or filling cups with beer.  One of the negatives of this design is it may be more likely to damage the cup and spill the beer and another is once people grow bored with it they will most likely return to the old fashioned pour but for now it is an innovative and effective example of emotional design.
http://builttolove.wordpress.com/
http://www.jnd.org/dn.mss/emotion_design.html
http://www.design-emotion.com/2010/01/25/the-power-of-nostalgia-in-advertising/



