Safe Design

Posted on October 31, 2012 by Thomas Scully 

Safe Design involves not the elimination of all risk, because that is impossible, but rather the minimization of potential risks and problems that may arise in a product.  It requires a good deal of thought in the design process in order to avoid all major problems that may arise.  The Law of Unitended Consequences states, “Almost all human actions have at least one unintended consequence.”  This is certainly true in design as desginers cannot predict everything that will come from their design.  Alfred Nobel had the intention of his invention, dynamite, being used in construction and excavation.  He realized soon that man would develop and use it as a weapon as time went on.
Although it is impossible to find all the possible outcomes or x’s, especially the negative ones, many of these various outcomes can be predicted and planned for.  Another thought is that not all unexpected outcomes will be negative.  A product could have an unexpected outcome that actually benefits the user or the product itself.  Also the negative results will not occur very frequently provided adequate time is spent planning for them, which it almost always is.  In cases where there are drastic negative results product liability comes in to play.  Product liability protects the customers in the case of poor design or failure to warn about know flaws in design.  In many cases the manufacturer is responsible for defects even if they were not known to ensure the customers are always protected.  This further ensures focus and time devoted to eliminating as many negative consequences as humanly possible.
Some well known flawed designs include the Titanic, The Challenger Space Shuttle, and the Dell Computer Notebook Battery, which needed to be recalled due to dangerous consequences.  A recall costs a company millions of dollars.  So a few extra hours or days to review and improve ceratain aspects of a design seems like a small price to pay in comparison to this cost.  These flawed designs resulted in disastrous consequences and will hopefully serve as an example to future designers to examine more aspects.  They will most definitely always serve as an example that no design is perfect and there are always consequences.  One interesting example of a product which many in the public view as dangerous is Hydrogen gas.  Hydrogen gas is in fact much safer, more abundant, and cleaner than gasoline and may prove to be a better source of energy.  It is not viewed positively because of one event, the explosion of the Hindenburg, which did not even explode because of the Hydrogen gas.  This shows how fear of danger can prevent even what could be beneficial designs from being created.  Safety will always and should always be one of the most if not the most important inputs in design.
http://www.scribd.com/doc/24862765/Normal-Accident-Theory-and-Design
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_liability
http://www.hydrogenhighway.ca.gov/facts/einsafety.pdf
https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=cHN1LmVkdXxlbmdpbmVlcmluZy1kZXNpZ258Z3g6NTVhMWNkMmM4ZmIyNmZhNg



